m and the Literary Imagination -- tHumanism and the Social: An Unclarified Relationship -- tPart V: Towards the Future -- tIntercultural Competence: A Humanistic Perspective -- tHumanism yet Once More: A View from the Other Side -- tLogocentrism and beyond: Some Concluding Remarks -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tNotes on the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is a breakthrough in illuminating humanism. For the first time it is presented in an intercultural perspective. It introduces Chinese, Indian, African, Islamic, and Western traditions into the intercultural discussion about basic issues of understanding the human world. By this means it recognizes different disciplinary perspectives: history, philosophy as well as religious, literary and gender studies. Special emphasis is put on the controversial relationship between humanism and religion. This complex network of argumentations is an answer to the challenge of cultural orientation at the age of globalization. Humanism is brought to life as a synthesis of transcultural values and a mutual and critical recognition of cultural differences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHumanismvCongresses. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCulture. 4aGlobalization. 4aHuman. 4aHumanities. 4aIntercultural Communication. 4aInterculturalism. 4aReligion. 4aReligious Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aCulture.  aGlobalization.  aHuman.  aHumanities.  aIntercultural Communication.  aInterculturalism.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.1 aArkoun, Muhammad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChakrabarty, Dipesh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChe